I remain a Christian for many reasonswhich I wont belabor here at the momentbut one is to dismantle the Old Order (which is, frankly, all our work to do) because it is wholly antithetical to the call and kingdom of Christ.
Jesus, in public, healed an outcast woman who suffered from chronic menstrual issues. So dont tell me he doesnt care about womens issues or feminism or what-have-you.

2: Antiqiated notions of gender roles were crushed along with the curse of sin through Jesuss death, resurrection and ascension. He literally instituted a new reality, yet evangelicalism (old white men) seeks to maintain the Old Order.

2: Most evangelical men are scared of interactions with women because they have no robust vision of sexuality. They suppress, suppress, suppress, and are thus pent up with sexual fury. Its honestly frightening. And this, this is why women cant be pastors or preachers.

2: I know too many Christians outraged about what is going on in Hollywood yet the same system is the framework of most evangelicalism. It stems (1) from an arrested theology of sex and the body and (2) the ancient patriarchal architecture.

2 (cont): The explicit denial of women in leadership, while they labor tirelessly behind the scenes, is to turn an eye to a complicity in systemic abuse and trauma. These lessons are actually in the Bible yet are never preached, these lessons never gleaned.

wrt 2: Evangelicalism has done everything it can to keep up the patriarchy (e.g. complementarianism) through an appeal to Gods created orderAdam as head, Eve as helpmate. This is the ultimate in Good Guy Ally-ism via an appeal to more grace and seeking peace.

wrt 1: Louis C.K. making I LOVE YOU, DADDY is basically how old, white, evangelical conservative men interpret scripture: self-righteous introspection regarding sin/transgression/etc. yet too proud/hypocritical to seek help. For them, the vocation is essentially the exorcism.

A couple of things to glean from today, for Christians: 1. Those who typically base their politics on biblical values have learned nothing from the Bible. 2. Its imperative that women are given positions of leadership in churches (esp. evangelical), i.e. pastor, preacher, etc.

http://1morefilmblog.com/2016/01/08/in-jackson-heights-wiseman-2015/
As a countertext, IN JACKSON HEIGHTS is a mosaic of American experience. Utopia dancing through our heads as the bourgeoisie stomp our feet.
Wiseman is practically seething throughout.
STATE LEGISLATURE really cracked Wiseman wide open for me.https://thefilmstage.com/features/state-legislature-frederick-wisemans-tome-on-democracy-in-modernity/
Essentially, he's reorienting us around a better vision of solidarity and goodness, utilizing the shadows of our shaped world as a lens.
He's a dialectic. His aim, justice. By contrasting embedded lives within the institutions they inhabit, he critiques and reshapes society.
His study of place/milieu holds in one hand a vision of flourishment and in the other the structures as they stand.
Wiseman isn't about institutions; he's about social fabricthe architectures of desire, i.e. utopias, that bolster or topple our Babels.
He's an extinct breed: an artist who actualizesby his investigationa vision of a Good world set right.
The two films I've seen of his I've also written about. His work has yielded some of my favorite writing experiences.
Wiseman on the tl always brings me hope

of that Original Trauma by it being inflicted upon the divinity as a full and final assault.

I want to see and feel and hear Somali, Sudanese, Iraqi, Egyptian, Libyan, Syrian, etc. cinema. 9/
and to see their cinema. We all agree that's our beloved medium's powerto create not just empathy but embeddedness. 8/
Now I'm planning dinner with them, a visit to their mosque, friendship. All day I've hungered to hear their voices, to see their faces. 7/
I spent most of last night at DFW airport hearing stories from Muslim families, many who have fled war and extremist atrocity. 6/
I want to promote the craftsmenship of our neighbors, that we'd see/hear/experience their storiesfrom their own lenses. 5/
Given recent events, I'm also looking into ways to support cinema from across the globe, esp from Muslim-majority nations 4/
I want to find ways to support what Elaine represents to many of her fans: a vision of equality and craftsmanship that includes all 3/
Here's the thing: I have planned since beginning this to give some back to orgs that support female filmmaking and criticism. 2/

I'll choose to be grateful. Hopefully I bettered lives around me. I'll do even better this year. Cheers all. And happy new year!
What does a year contain? I have such a bad memory. There was so much more. All in all, 2016 is a period of time. It held bad and good.
had personal and professional breakthroughs that bettered me, met some truly wonderful people, & saw the birth of my sweet lil Walter!
profiled Travolta & now want to write a book, truly discovered De Palma, moved to Fort Worth (finally!), developed mean ping pong skills..
made $ (a v small amt) for a piece, discovered Elaine May, ate an ungodly Amy of donuts, finally fell at the knees of Jerry Lewis...
planted a church, moved twice, had the best year of my marriage, saw a friend thru hardest period of his life, watched first Godard...
argued w/a lot of friends & family abt Trump and America, went to Portland and met @JoelMayward, voted progressive for 1st time...
saw 1st movie in a theater w/my son, threw my wife a surprise bday party, wrote more than I thought possible (11 reviews in a single wk!)...
watched MCCABE & MRS MILLER on 35mm, sat in the same theater with and walked past Jessica Harper, was poked by a used needle...
2016: met Steven Soderbergh, attended my first film festivals, met Ed Lachman, lived w/in-laws for 6 mos, ate cat food w/Joel Potrykus...
